295","after 1312":"after 1312","Wadden Hall, Waltham,Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England","Dover, Dover district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Dover, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Dover, Kent, England":"Dover, Kent, England","Vale of White Horse, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Vale of White Horse, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Atte","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Pakistan and Egypt): variant of   Ata  .","West African (Ghana): from an Akan (Fante) male personal name denoting a twin. Compare   Arthur  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ata","meanings":["Turkish: ornamental name, nickname, or relationship name from <i>ata</i> ‘father, elder’.","Muslim (mainly Egypt): from a personal name based on Arabic <i>ʿaṭā</i> ‘gift’ (understood as ‘gift from God’). Compare   Atallah   and   Atta  ."]}]},{"name":"Halle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Rejean, Marcel, Andre, Arianne, Armand, Camille, Fernand, Gaspard, Laurent.","German and English: variant of   Hall  .","French (also <b>Hallé</b>): topographic name from Old French <i>halle</i> ‘covered market’, from <i>halla</i> ‘covered room’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hall","meanings":["English, Scottish, Irish, German, Norwegian, and Danish: from Middle English <i>hall</i> (Old English <i>heall</i>), Middle High German <i>halle</i>, Old Norse <i>hǫll</i> all meaning ‘hall’ (a spacious residence), hence a topographic name for someone who lived in or near a hall or an occupational name for a servant employed at a hall. In some cases it may be a habitational name from any of the places called with this word, which in some parts of Germany and Austria in the Middle Ages also denoted a salt mine. Hall is one of the commonest and most widely distributed of English surnames, bearing witness to the importance of the hall as a feature of the medieval village. The English surname has been established in Ireland since the 14th century, and, according to MacLysaght, has become numerous in Ulster since the 17th century.","Swedish: ornamental or topographic name from <i>hall</i> ‘hall’ (a spacious residence), or a habitational name from a placename containing the element <i>hall</i> ‘rock’ (from Old Norse <i>hallr</i>).","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 何 and 賀, see   He   1 and 2."]},{"name":"Hallee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Armand, Fernand, Henri, Napoleon, Renald, Urbain.","French Canadian (also <b>Hallée</b>): variant of <b>Hallé</b> (see   Halle   3)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Atte Halle was born about 1275, in Dover, Kent, England as the son of Sir William Atte Halle, I. He married Annabel England about 1299, in Dover, Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died after 1312."},"et":{"Abt 1275–after 1312":"umbes 1275–pärast 1312","1275–1312":"1275–1312","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1300–1399":"1300–1399","1235–1275":"1235–1275","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","Abt 1299":"umbes 1299","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","Abt 1275":"umbes 1275","about 1295":"umbes 1295","after 1312":"pärast 1312","Wadden Hall, Waltham,Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England","Dover, Dover district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Dover, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Dover, Kent, England":"Dover, Kent, England","Vale of White Horse, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Vale of White Horse, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1275–after 1312":"noin 1275–1312 jälkeen","1275–1312":"1275–1312","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1300–1399":"1300–1399","1235–1275":"1235–1275","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","Abt 1299":"noin 1299","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","Abt 1275":"noin 1275","about 1295":"noin 1295","after 1312":"1312 jälkeen","Wadden Hall, Waltham,Canterbury, Kent, England":"Canterbury, Kent, England","Dover, Dover district, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Dover, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Dover, Kent, England":"Dover, Kent, England","Vale of White Horse, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Vale of White Horse, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1275–after 1312":"environ 1275–après 1312","1275–1312":"1275–1312","1280–1312":"1280–1312","1295–1361":"1295–1361","1300–1399":"1300–1399","1235–1275":"1235–1275","1275":"1275","1361":"1361","1295":"1295","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1312":"1312","1235":"1235","Abt 1299":"environ 1299","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","Abt 1275":"environ 1275"